00:14:48.250 --> 00:14:52.300
a Paleolithic memo
to self or a prayer.

00:14:52.300 --> 00:14:56.230
We really don't know what it means,
but we do know that it was created

00:14:56.230 --> 00:15:00.110
by human beings because
after all they signed it.

00:15:00.110 --> 00:15:07.830 position:56%
And that's one of the things that's
so, to us in the present age missing

00:15:07.830 --> 00:15:10.250
from moving from print
to digital is the

00:15:10.250 --> 00:15:13.880
since that machines actually have
some human quality and I want

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:15.800
to talk about that,
because you'll see

00:15:15.800 --> 00:15:20.540
that if this is a Paleolithic
selfie, the impulse to take selfies

00:15:20.540 --> 00:15:23.570
and leave records of yourself
is just as vibrant today,

00:15:23.570 --> 00:15:26.100
in fact it's more vibrant
in many ways.

00:15:26.100 --> 00:15:28.210
But the important thing
about technology is

00:15:28.210 --> 00:15:32.590
that technology is simply a tool,
it is an extension of human will.

00:15:32.590 --> 00:15:36.630
It actually has no power of its
own other than what we grab to it.

00:15:36.630 --> 00:15:39.310
So I'm not at all a
technological determinist.

00:15:39.310 --> 00:15:41.700
I don't believe that technologies
will make us do anything

00:15:41.700 --> 00:15:44.900
and the machines are
inherently threatening to us.

00:15:44.900 --> 00:15:46.750
If machines are threatening
to us it's

00:15:46.750 --> 00:15:48.980
because we are threatening
to ourselves.

00:15:48.980 --> 00:15:51.390
So that's why I'm very
optimistic about trying

00:15:51.390 --> 00:15:54.120 position:56%
to master memory in the digital age.

00:15:54.120 --> 00:15:58.290
Nothing is predetermined for us.

00:15:58.290 --> 00:16:02.000
You know, the reason I believe
and this is my personal opinion,

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.380
the reason that we invented
memory technologies to begin with

00:16:05.380 --> 00:16:08.060
and the moment in history
when we did was when I think

00:16:08.060 --> 00:16:10.220
of when the Garden of Eden moment.

00:16:10.220 --> 00:16:13.260
The moment whenever that was
in history when human beings

00:16:13.260 --> 00:16:17.060
and clearly it was homosapiens,
not just, not just Neanderthals

00:16:17.060 --> 00:16:20.100
because they didn't leave
records of their thoughts behind.

00:16:20.100 --> 00:16:25.380 position:56%
But when human beings finally or
realized that they were going to die

00:16:25.380 --> 00:16:29.050
and not just so that other
members of their species would die,

00:16:29.050 --> 00:16:31.090
but that they personally
would die and that

00:16:31.090 --> 00:16:33.810
at some point children
would grow up knowing

00:16:33.810 --> 00:16:36.280
that they too were destined to die.

00:16:36.280 --> 00:16:39.110
And I think it's the reason that
we started to invent technologies

00:16:39.110 --> 00:16:41.100
that essentially cheat death.

00:16:41.100 --> 00:16:43.870
And I think that if we, I
think memory technologies are

00:16:43.870 --> 00:16:46.010
in fact wonderful ways
to cheat death

00:16:46.010 --> 00:16:49.810
and that drives a lot
of their application.

00:16:49.810 --> 00:16:53.920
Technologies are also always
designed to solve a problem

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:57.600
or sometimes to meet a demand
or market demand for example.

00:16:57.600 --> 00:16:59.690
And I'll show you some
examples of that.

00:16:59.690 --> 00:17:03.000
But the think about clever human
beings and inventing tools is

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:06.050
that we solve one problem
and we create three

00:17:06.050 --> 00:17:08.420
that we would never
have anticipated.

00:17:08.420 --> 00:17:11.340
And we know when a
technology is truly successful

00:17:11.340 --> 00:17:13.410
because then it gets
used for many things

00:17:13.410 --> 00:17:16.360
that the inventors would
never have anticipated.

00:17:16.360 --> 00:17:20.220
And we fall into this sort of
dizzying vertigo of lots of uses

00:17:20.220 --> 00:17:23.160
