one had anticipated

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:26.910
and this is what I call the havoc
phase of technology adoption.

00:17:26.910 --> 00:17:28.680
And you know when technology
is really successful

00:17:28.680 --> 00:17:32.750
when it reeks extraordinary havoc
in the first couple of generations.

00:17:32.750 --> 00:17:34.440
So judging by that, I would say

00:17:34.440 --> 00:17:36.800
that print was a hugely
successful technology

00:17:36.800 --> 00:17:40.030
because it created huge
havoc after its invention

00:17:40.030 --> 00:17:45.500 position:56%
and certainly digital technology is
also dismayingly successful and it's

00:17:45.500 --> 00:17:48.350
at a dismayingly widespread
havoc phase.

00:17:48.350 --> 00:17:51.390
So the signs of havoc phase
and we can talk about this

00:17:51.390 --> 00:17:55.130
if you want is always a
certain amount of infatuation

00:17:55.130 --> 00:17:57.070 position:56%
with the new technology, infatuation

00:17:57.070 --> 00:17:59.310
with the technology
for its own sake.

00:17:59.310 --> 00:18:03.540
A lot of fear about the technology,
a lot of [inaudible] inadvertent,

00:18:03.540 --> 00:18:05.820
sorry information inflation.

00:18:05.820 --> 00:18:09.760
So we actually start using
technology to start creating a lot

00:18:09.760 --> 00:18:12.300
of information that then we
don't know what to do with,

00:18:12.300 --> 00:18:15.260
that's the inflation phase.

00:18:15.260 --> 00:18:19.080
And we always find over
time after a couple

00:18:19.080 --> 00:18:23.100
of native generations have grown
up with whatever technology

00:18:23.100 --> 00:18:27.840
that we actually are able to
tap in a new human potentials,

00:18:27.840 --> 00:18:30.420
express something new about
the new human experience

00:18:30.420 --> 00:18:31.720
through these new technologies

00:18:31.720 --> 00:18:34.140
and that's why they're
so valuable to us.

00:18:34.140 --> 00:18:36.090
So we have new writers.

00:18:36.090 --> 00:18:38.150
We certainly have new audiences

00:18:38.150 --> 00:18:42.250
and we also have changed
perceptions about human destiny.

00:18:42.250 --> 00:18:44.120
Another thing that I learned
working at the Library

00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:47.800
of Congress is how very powerful
the invention of moving image,

00:18:47.800 --> 00:18:51.350 position:56%
even silent film was in changing
the way that people were assimilated

00:18:51.350 --> 00:18:53.730
into American culture
for example and the way

00:18:53.730 --> 00:18:55.390 position:56%
that people started to tell stories.

00:18:55.390 --> 00:19:00.430
And the influence that, that movie
making narrative had subsequently

00:19:00.430 --> 00:19:03.040
on the way we think,
the way we perceive time

00:19:03.040 --> 00:19:05.700
and also the way we write.

00:19:05.700 --> 00:19:07.190
So I want to talk a little bit

00:19:07.190 --> 00:19:10.790
about some the things we
can expect from technology.

00:19:10.790 --> 00:19:15.500
Technology always inspires
fear and also excitement

00:19:15.500 --> 00:19:18.130
and some people praise a
new information technology

00:19:18.130 --> 00:19:20.490
as disruptive and creative.

00:19:20.490 --> 00:19:21.800
I would say that's my tribe

00:19:21.800 --> 00:19:24.830
of Silcon Valley technologist
where I live among now.

00:19:24.830 --> 00:19:27.500
And others condemn it as
disruptive and destructive.

00:19:27.500 --> 00:19:32.600
And I want to talk about why both
those things are a little bit too

00:19:32.600 --> 00:19:34.520
extreme and unrealistic.

00:19:34.520 --> 00:19:39.070
But I want to take as this sort
of granddaddy example of this sort

00:19:39.070 --> 00:19:40.600
of [inaudible] of technology.

00:19:40.600 --> 00:19:45.080
Socrates, who famously warned
that the invention of writing,

00:19:45.080 --> 00:19:47.770
something I think we all love
ourselves, that the invention

00:19:47.770 --> 00:19:49.950
of writing would lead to
ignorance and ultimately

00:19:49.950 --> 00:19:52.010
to the death of memory itself.

00:19:52.010 --> 00:19:56.220
And here I want to quote
Socrates, "For this invention,

00:19:56.220 --> 00:19:59.280
writing will produce forgetfulness
in the minds of those who learn

00:19:59.280 --> 00:20:02.600
to use it, because they will
not practice their memory.

00:20:02.600 --> 00:20:05.490
Their trust in writing
produced by external characters

00:20:05.490 --> 00:20:08.460
which are no part of themselves
will discourage the use

00:20:08.460 --> 00:20:10.490
of their own memory within them.

00:20:10.490 --> 00:20:14.820
Users have invented an elixir
not of memory but of reminding.

00:20:14.820 --> 00:20:17.730
And you offer your pupils
the appearance of wisdom,

00:20:17.730 --> 00:20:21.670 position:56%
but not true wisdom for they will
read many things without instruction

00:20:21.670 --> 00:20:24.410
and will therefore seem to
know many things when they are

00:20:24.410 --> 00:20:26.640
for the most part ignorant
and hard to get along

00:20:26.640 --> 00:20:30.810
with since they are not
wise but appear wise."

00:20:30.810 --> 00:20:32.830
I think we could say as
I've heard many parents say,

00:20:32.830 --> 00:20:36.200
they don't know anything, they
know where to look things up.

00:20:36.200 --> 00:20:39.690
So I think that's actually
a very common reaction.

00:20:39.690 --> 00:20:41.730
But in my mind Socrates
got it wrong.

00:20:41.730 --> 00:20:45.240
It was actually the societies that
adopted writing that progressed

00:20:45.240 --> 00:20:48.580
and extended the reach of knowledge
and as we will see the reach

00:20:48.580 --> 00:20:53.430
of knowledge is also the reach of
self-autonomy and self-liberation.

00:20:53.430 --> 00:20:56.440
And after all let's not forget
if Plato had not been writing

00:20:56.440 --> 00:21:00.590 position:56%
down what Socrates said, we wouldn't
know that Socrates was ever alive

00:21:00.590 --> 00:21:02.050
and Socrates was a great ironist.

00:21:02.050 --> 00:21:04.180
I'm sure he knew that
he would be immortal

00:21:04.180 --> 00:21:06.090
through the words of somebody else.

00:21:06.090 --> 00:21:10.640 position:56%
But I love this example of
Socrates because he points out first

00:21:10.640 --> 00:21:12.200
and foremost, the moral hazard

00:21:12.200 --> 00:21:15.090
of actually outsourcing our
memory to anything else.

00:21:15.090 --> 00:21:20.660
Once it leaves our physical custody
then in fact it begins to do things

00:21:20.660 --> 00:21:22.130 position:56%
that we don't have any control over.

00:21:22.130 --> 00:21:24.600
And I think that's one
of the underlying fears

00:21:24.600 --> 00:21:26.990
that we're encountering
now in the digital age

00:21:26.990 --> 00:21:30.890 position:56%
when people put personal information
online for example, it's personal,

00:21:30.890 --> 00:21:33.080
they're sharing it
personally and they don't

00:21:33.080 --> 00:21:36.760
yet understand that's it's a
commercially owned platform

00:21:36.760 --> 00:21:40.780
that is using that data
for its own purposes.

00:21:40.780 --> 00:21:42.160
So you know, the thing

00:21:42.160 --> 00:21:44.300
about technology is no one
can predict how it's going

00:21:44.300 --> 00:21:47.990
to be naturalized by those
curious beings, humans.

00:21:47.990 --> 00:21:51.580
And I want to take a case in point,
one very familiar to all of you

00:21:51.580 --> 00:21:54.600
and that is the case of Johannes
Gutenberg, the goldsmith.

00:21:54.600 --> 00:21:59.270
He invented movable type and he met
it to meet a very specific demand.

00:21:59.270 --> 00:22:03.270
He didn't actually intend to invent
the Renaissance and the reformation

00:22:03.270 --> 00:22:05.820
which is what historians
see in retrospect.

00:22:05.820 --> 00:22:08.400
He actually wanted to
create, he didn't want

00:22:08.400 --> 00:22:11.180
to create even a new
fangled technology.

00:22:11.180 --> 00:22:14.310
He was trying to produce a
cheaper and faster version

00:22:14.310 --> 00:22:18.370
of an old fangled thing, this
thing, the giant bible of mites.

00:22:18.370 --> 00:22:20.120
And those of you have been

00:22:20.120 --> 00:22:25.390
to the Jefferson building will know
what an amazing job he did knocking

00:22:25.390 --> 00:22:27.420
off the old form.

00:22:27.420 --> 00:22:31.020
He wanted to give people something
that looked like this only cheaper

00:22:31.020 --> 00:22:34.790 position:56%
and faster, so he was market demand.

00:22:34.790 --> 00:22:37.880
And I know as a historian
of technology and ideas

00:22:37.880 --> 00:22:41.600
that within 50 years the early
doctors of this technology,

00:22:41.600 --> 00:22:44.310
you can say the early
print adopters,

00:22:44.310 --> 00:22:47.900
the early print tech adopters
that ran with the technology

00:22:47.900 --> 00:22:50.290
of most innovative and
effective ways come

00:22:50.290 --> 00:22:53.310
in two tribes, then as they do now.

00:22:53.310 --> 00:22:57.800
Initially, there's a
flourishing of pornography

00:22:57.800 --> 00:23:01.770
and there was then the pornographic
images of the Pope for example,

00:23:01.770 --> 00:23:05.570
really quite vivid and
were highly in demand.

00:23:05.570 --> 00:23:09.300
And the second group are what
I would call euphemistically

00:23:09.300 --> 00:23:11.170
ideological dissidence.

00:23:11.170 --> 00:23:13.910
In the case of the
Renaissance there were people

00:23:13.910 --> 00:23:16.530
who were protesting the
power of the Papacy.

00:23:16.530 --> 00:23:19.530
And we call them because
they've become respectable,

00:23:19.530 --> 00:23:23.890
we call them Protestants now
but in fact at the time they,

00:23:23.890 --> 00:23:28.870
they were arguing for ideological
and I'd say theological utopias

00:23:28.870 --> 00:23:34.020
that actually would be very
familiar to us from the headlines.

00:23:34.020 --> 00:23:37.230
There wasn't anything that
Isis had invented in the way

00:23:37.230 --> 00:23:40.810
of human enforcement and
persuasion that wasn't used

00:23:40.810 --> 00:23:43.140
by Protestant sex at that time.

00:23:43.140 --> 00:23:47.080
And the way they got a grip over
the human imagination was in fact

00:23:47.080 --> 00:23:49.200
through the way of use
of printing technology.

00:23:49.200 --> 00:23:52.350
Not that everybody read but all
you had to do was talk to somebody,

00:23:52.350 --> 00:23:55.450 position:56%
who had talked to somebody who had
read something that the Protestants,

00:23:55.450 --> 00:23:57.950
these dissidents have published.

00:23:57.950 --> 00:24:00.660
But you know, there was always
more there was always an upside,

00:24:00.660 --> 00:24:02.260
not just a downside.

00:24:02.260 --> 00:24:04.710
And my favorite upside story

00:24:04.710 --> 00:24:10.400 position:56%
of the printing revolution is this
man Michel de Montaigne who was born

00:24:10.400 --> 00:24:13.430
in 1533 and you could say
that he was among the first

00:24:13.430 --> 00:24:15.950
of the born print natives.

00:24:15.950 --> 00:24:20.720
And he became an author,
he wrote his famous essays.

00:24:20.720 --> 00:24:24.660
He became an author
because there was printing.

00:24:24.660 --> 00:24:27.100
If there weren't printing he
would've written those essays

00:24:27.100 --> 00:24:30.030
as manuscripts letters and
sent them to his family.

00:24:30.030 --> 00:24:33.100
Instead he wrote his essays, he
published them, he published them

00:24:33.100 --> 00:24:36.520
over many additions
over his lifetime.

00:24:36.520 --> 00:24:39.860
And the whole genre of personal
essay that he invented was

00:24:39.860 --> 00:24:43.550
so popular that it has never ever
gone out of print until this day.

00:24:43.550 --> 00:24:47.570
That's something that all authors
in new genres can aspire to.

00:24:47.570 --> 00:24:52.680
And if fact one of the things that
really struck me about Montaigne is

00:24:52.680 --> 00:24:56.750
that he didn't just invent a new
genre, he invented a new appetite

00:24:56.750 --> 00:24:59.610
and a new way of readers
thinking about themselves

00:24:59.610 --> 00:25:02.490
and altering the way they
thought about themselves

00:25:02.490 --> 00:25:04.200
and what they were capable of.

00:25:04.200 --> 00:25:09.730
I want to move quickly, we're just
going to jump over a few centuries

00:25:09.730 --> 00:25:12.420
and talk about our very
dear friend and benefactor,

00:25:12.420 --> 00:25:16.560
sort of a patron saint of libraries
in this country, Thomas Jefferson.

00:25:16.560 --> 00:25:19.820
Because by the time of the
enlightenment in the 18 Century,

00:25:19.820 --> 00:25:23.110
knowledge itself, the thing that
was passed down through books

00:25:23.110 --> 00:25:28.500 position:56%
and other forms was redefined not as
something that was self-reflective

00:25:28.500 --> 00:25:30.900
where we could learn about
ourselves and learn about God

00:25:30.900 --> 00:25:35.200
but it was also a political agent,
it was a way of changing the world.

00:25:35.200 --> 00:25:37.570
And I think because
we've grown up you know,

00:25:37.570 --> 00:25:39.980
in the legacy of Thomas
Jefferson we failed

00:25:39.980 --> 00:25:43.400
to understand how enormously
radical that was the time,

00:25:43.400 --> 00:25:46.660
the idea that knowledge itself
was an agent of progress.

00:25:46.660 --> 00:25:49.440
I mean it was a very
irreligious idea in many ways,

00:25:49.440 --> 00:25:52.850
the idea that you wanted to change
the world, not to know the world.

00:25:52.850 --> 00:25:58.010
But it was widespread and it has
taken over I think with the spread

00:25:58.010 --> 00:26:01.860
of western thought and western
information technologies.

00:26:01.860 --> 00:26:04.950
It's widely acknowledged now
that the world is something

00:26:04.950 --> 00:26:08.010
that we can change
through information.

00:26:08.010 --> 00:26:13.730
The other thing that we do
know about what happened

00:26:13.730 --> 00:26:17.930 position:56%
with enlightenment view of
knowledge is it imposed entirely new

00:26:17.930 --> 00:26:19.770
responsibilities on the government

00:26:19.770 --> 00:26:23.270
to provide access information
to its citizens.

00:26:23.270 --> 00:26:26.440
There was no way that Jefferson
and his cohort believed

00:26:26.440 --> 00:26:29.740
that we could be good citizens
without being well-informed

00:26:29.740 --> 00:26:32.570
and so we have public libraries,
we have the freedom of the press

00:26:32.570 --> 00:26:34.420 position:56%
and other things that we know about.

00:26:34.420 --> 00:26:38.460
The thing that fails to get lauded
as much as freedom of the press

00:26:38.460 --> 00:26:40.480
and libraries as the responsibility

00:26:40.480 --> 00:26:42.630
of the government is the
responsibility of citizens

00:26:42.630 --> 00:26:46.720
to stay informed, that
was a part of the equation

00:26:46.720 --> 00:26:49.120
that we don't talk
about very much today.

00:26:49.120 --> 00:26:53.170 position:56%
But it is in fact the vision behind
the people who invented the internet

00:26:53.170 --> 00:26:56.510
and certainly the people
who put together Google.

00:26:56.510 --> 00:26:58.950
I mean they wanted to
organize the world's knowledge

00:26:58.950 --> 00:27:02.300
so that people could have access
to it and make it easy to find.

00:27:02.300 --> 00:27:04.650
Things haven't turned out
exactly the way they planned

00:27:04.650 --> 00:27:06.540
but that's just in
the nature of things.

00:27:06.540 --> 00:27:14.870
I want to talk briefly about this
boom, this is a reading room one

00:27:14.870 --> 00:27:16.260
of the earliest reading rooms

00:27:16.260 --> 00:27:18.650
of 19th Century, in
Paris in [inaudible].

00:27:18.650 --> 00:27:22.120 position:56%
It was built in 1838 and you can see

00:27:22.120 --> 00:27:25.790
that it embodies very revolutionary
ideas of accessed information.

00:27:25.790 --> 00:27:28.860
Before this there was no student
reading room at the university,

00:27:28.860 --> 00:27:31.880
they used to have to take
books back to their garrets.

00:27:31.880 --> 00:27:35.030
But now they, he built
this large reading room

